  To write a program that prints hello world in Visual Basic, you will need to use the Console application object and its Write() method to display text in a message box or similar user interface component.
Here is an example of such code: 
```C#
using System;
class Program {
    static void Main(string[] args) {
        // Printing "Hello World" using WriteLine();
        Console.WriteLine("Hello World");

        // Printing "The current directory is:" using WriteLine();
        string path = Environment.GetFolderPath(Environment.SpecialFolder.Desktop);
        Console.WriteLine("The current directory is: " + path);
     }
}
```

This code first creates an instance of the class Program (which inherits from `System::Console`), then calls the `Main` function with no arguments which starts the execution flow by calling the static WriteLine() method on the Console object, printing out "Hello World".

In addition, this code also demonstrates another feature of the Console application - the ability to output information about the environment it runs under. Specifically, this code uses the GetFolderPath() method of the Environment class to retrieve the path where the executable file resides, and displays it as-is in a message box.</s>

