  The most common issues in international commercial arbitrations include:
Conflicts of law – different legal systems may apply; 
Enforceability concerns - parties might face difficulty enforcing arbitral awards abroad; 
Lack of impartiality or independence of judges/arbitrators; 
Inadequate resources and procedures for resolving complex disputes; 
Dispute resolution costs which may be higher than those associated with litigating. 
These challenges often lead to delays in dispute settlements due to uncertainties surrounding enforceable decisions taken by an independent tribunal. Some recommendations for addressing these difficulties could include adopting uniform laws and rules to ensure consistency between jurisdictions, increasing transparency in the appointment process for arbitrators and other experts who help resolve the matter quickly, introducing alternative dispute resolution methods such as mediation and conciliation, as well as establishing mechanisms for resolving procedural matters without delay. Above all it is important that each party understand their rights and obligations under the terms agreed upon, and seek professional advice where necessary. This will significantly reduce chances of misunderstandings leading to further complications during the proceedings.</s>

  International commercial arbitration faces a number of challenges when dealing with cross-border disputes. These include:
1) Lack of familiarity with foreign laws or legal systems; 
2) Difficulty in obtaining evidence from abroad;
3) Language barriers;
4) Differences in culture and business practices;
