 Seed means initial condition and its value affects the results of subsequent computations performed on that data set (for example sorting algorithms). In order for these algorithm to work properly we need an appropriate initialization point which is usually referred as seed or input parameters. Without such an information it will not be able to compute accurate output for the given inputs.
For example: We want to sort an array using bubble-sort method. It needs two elements as arguments for its implementation like "a[0],a[1]". But how can this array be sorted initially? To achieve that, you would use another argument called "seed" and assign random values for those first two indices before starting actual computation process. The code may look something like below: 
// Initialize some arbitrary seed numbers 
let x = Math.floor(Math.random()*10) + 1; 
let y = Math.floor(Math.random()*10) + 1; 

function swapElementsInArrayAtIndex(arr, idx_first, idx_second){ 
  let tempElementAtIndexFirst = arr[idx_first]; 
  let tempElementAtIndexSecond = arr[idx_second]; 
  arr[idx_first] = tempElementAtIndexSecond; 
  arr[idx_second] = tempElementAtIndexFirst; 
}

// Start bubbling loop from the specified seed  
for(var j=x ;j<=y; j++) {   
  // Iterate over each element of the current index  
  if (arr[j - 1] > arr[j]){ 
     // Swap two elements at same index 
     swapElementsInArrayAtIndex(arr, j-1, j);  
  } 
  // Print the current value 
