  The causes of the French Revolution were complex and interrelated but can be summarized as follows: 
- Social inequality in France at the time was high, leading to resentment among many members of society, especially the working class known as the "Third Estate" (so named because they did not belong to either the nobility or clergy). They faced taxes while having few rights or political representation;
- A lack of effective leadership within the government also contributed to the tensions that eventually led to revolution. Many citizens believed that the King's policies had become increasingly corrupt, leading to widespread dissatisfaction with his rule;
- Economic conditions also played a major part, particularly a financial crisis that caused significant inflation, poverty, and unemployment across the country. This resulted in a deepening sense of mistrust between different social classes;
- Finally, there were the Enlightenment ideas which advocated for equality and representative governance, providing inspiration and a philosophical justification for revolt. These ideals fueled an anti-monarchist movement and ultimately brought about a complete change in how power was exercised in France.
The main consequence of the French Revolution is its long lasting impact on Western democracy. It laid the foundations for the establishment of republicanism as well as constitutional monarchy and separation of church and state in Europe. Its influence continues to be felt today in the form of universal human rights and other progressive values that are enshrined in national constitutions around the world. However, it has been argued that these same principles have created a new set of problems by eroding traditional community bonds and family structures. Despite this, the idea of freedom remains an important ideal and the French Revolution continues to hold relevance even in the present day.</s>

