 Big-O notation is a mathematical expression used to describe the upper bound of the growth rate of a function. It typically describes how quickly a given algorithm or data structure increases with respect to the input size, and it lets you compare the performance of two algorithms or functions based on their worst-case complexity in terms of time and space requirements. Here's an example:

