  if (n <= 0 || n == 1) return n
  return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2)
}
// Printing the result for increasing values of `n`
for i in stride(from: 3, to: 50, by: 1) {
   print("\(fibonacci(i))")
}
```
The first line defines the fibonacci() function that takes an integer as its argument, returning its value at index n. The second line initializes the recursion call with n = 2, which means that all calls from then on will begin with recursion until we reach n = 0, which represents the base case and marks the end of the recursion process. In this way, the time required to calculate each number grows exponentially. The third line displays the results using the stride function, which prints out successive numbers in increments of one. Finally, the last line just loops through those numbers up to fifty. If you ran this code snippet, you would see something like "84" printed every iteration (the sum of all five Fibonacci numbers smaller than or equal to 2). Notice that the larger the value of n becomes, the longer does it take for the recursive function to finish calculating each number because the amount of work involved keeps growing rapidly. This illustrates the concept of Big-Oh notation, where an equation can be

