  The factors contributing to the Union's eventual victory were: 
1) Manpower advantage: the North had a larger population and was able to mobilize more troops than the South; 
2) Resources advantage: the Union had access to a large number of industrial materials, which enabled them to build better weapons and equipment than the Confederates; 
3) Leadership: Lincoln proved to be an effective leader during the war while Jefferson Davis failed to provide clear direction for his forces;
4) Strategy: Grant and Sherman devised strategies such as the Anaconda Plan, which focused on capturing important cities along key rivers, thus cutting off supply lines and resources from the Confederacy;
5) Military technology: The introduction of railroads allowed faster movement of men and supplies over long distances, while the use of ironclads made naval blockades more efficient; 
6) Diplomatic efforts: Abraham Lincoln issued several executive orders freeing slaves and promising federal protection for black citizens in certain areas. This encouraged southern slaves to defect and join the Union side, reducing Southern manpower;
7) Morale boost: Several Northern victories helped increase morale among its soldiers and allies, resulting in higher enlistment rates. 
8) Political pressure at home: Anti-war sentiment was growing back in the north, so any decisive victories by either side would help garner political support and funding needed to continue the fight. 
9) Weakening of the South: With fewer men and limited resources, the Confederate army began suffering setback after setback until they were ultimately defeated.</s>

